# **Delegation Areas / Categories**

## **Personal**

**Area 1: Physical Health**  
Anything that improves the person's physical health. This could include medical stuff (like doctors or medication), exercise, food (if for health reasons, not just booking a fancy restaurant), etc.

One-time task examples:   
Research personal trainers who do mobility program design and coaching via Zoom.

Recurring task examples:   
Book meal delivery from a local service every week.

**Area 2: Mental Health**  
Typically this would entail massages, therapy, and certain types of vacations or travel. It can also be small practices like adding a time buffer to avoid meeting overwhelm.

One-time task examples:   
Book me a Thai massage during my business trip to NYC.

Recurring task examples:   
Once per quarter, book a week-long nature retreat in a cabin somewhere Instagrammable within a 6 hour flight from NYC.

**Area 3: Relationships**  
Any tasks related to helping the client maintain or develop new connections with friends and family. Excludes work-related contacts, generally.

One-time task examples:   
Set up a recurring call with my sister for 60 minutes each month, on a weekend.

Recurring task examples:   
Buy gifts for all the important people in my life on their birthdays.

**Area 4: Personal Finance**  
Any activity related to personal and family money management. Includes investing, credit cards, banking, research of financial products like loans, etc.

One-time task examples:   
Figure out the best way to use my current credit card loyalty points to book a flying apartment on Etihad to Dubai in February. If it takes more than 2 hours, hire someone (up to $200) who specializes in reward hacking.

Recurring task examples:   
Any time I make a new startup investment, add the information to the investment tracking Airtable and add relevant documents to tax folder in Dropbox

**Area 5: Learning / PKM**  
Any task oriented around helping the client learn something new or store knowledge from research, etc. 

One-time task examples:   
Log into my Audible account and buy the Systems Bible by John Gall.

Recurring task examples:   
Once a month, search blogs X/Y/Z and Pinterest for any interesting new tiny house designers, and update my Notion database of tiny houses. Then email the links to any really good ones.

**Area 6: Passion Projects**  
If a client is spending a lot of creative time and energy on something that they're not paid for, that's a good indication this is a passion project. A personal hobby, working on a book/painting/home remodeling project, etc.

One-time task examples:   
Research publishers of children's books and find ones that have received good reviews for working with first-time authors. Collect those and add links to the authors and their books in a G Sheet.

Recurring task examples:   
Search Facebook marketplace once a month for \[insert obscure make/model car or motorcycle\] and forward me the content if you find one for sale.

**Area 7: Bucket List**  
Things that are very important to the client to do before they die, i.e. major life goals and experiences. The tasks connected to these may be minor (e.g. researching travel options or scheduling a consultation), but the outcome is important.

One-time task examples:   
Design and cost out options for a 10-day African safari trip.

Recurring task examples:   
Every month, message the Antarctic cruise line I like for cancellations to see if we can get on the fully-booked March trip for next year.

**Area 8:  Experiences & Travel**  
Travel-related tasks and experiential ones, such as a wildlife tour or Japanese pottery-making class.

One-time task examples:   
Research and book a hotel near the beach in Canggu Bali near a high-end gym

Recurring task examples:   
When booking a new trip more than one week, create a Notion page with recommended restaurants/attractions, and star them in Google Maps

### 

## **Business**

**Area 9: Admin**  
General administrative activities relating to the client's business, rather than their personal life.

One-time task examples:   
Schedule a meeting with from FounderPath or Lighter Capital to see what our revenue-based financing package would look like given our metrics.

Recurring task examples:   
When a new lead is added to Airtable and tagged "VIP", research and fill out the rest of columns when they aren’t automatically enriched by AI.

**Area 10: Finance**  
Activities related to a business's finances, such as invoicing, reconciling books, and so on.

One-time task examples:   
Help Tim switch us from \[X\] to Bench/Pilot

Recurring task examples:   
Pull expenses monthly from our Mercury account and label them in a Google Sheet for our accountant.

**Area 11: People**  
Hiring, maintaining company culture, facilitating 360 reviews for employees, organizing company off-sites or events, and so on.

One-time task examples:   
Set up job listing on Ashby based on scraped descriptions from similar jobs given to an LLM 

Recurring task examples:   
Once per quarter, identify a gift \<$200 and send one to everyone on the team who isn't a contractor. Email Sara 3 options and she can have final say.

**Area 12: Marketing**  
Activities relating to organic, brand, paid ads, SEO, content strategy, newsletters, thought leadership, social media, and other forms of marketing.

One-time task examples:   
Subscribe to all our competitors email lists and have them forwarded to email-intelligence@startup.co.

Recurring task examples:   
Pull best performing social media posts from people in industry X each week. Put these in a spreadsheet.

**Area 13: Sales**  
Activities relating to researching sales prospects, enriching data pipelines, analyzing sales funnels, creating outbound sales messaging, etc.

One-time task examples:   
Create a list of enriched prospects using Clay and Apollo for US startups that raised at least $Xm in Q2 2024

Recurring task examples:   
Periodic prospecting via LinkedIn Sales Navigator scraping / etc 

**Area 14: Product**  
Activities related to a company's products and services, including competitive research or facilitating interviews with current/prospective customers.

One-time task examples:   
Post ads on Facebook for demo/behavior group \[X\] to get 10 prospective users on a 60-minute UX interview so we can talk about their pain points. Have them self-schedule with Calendly after answering a Typeform with answers X/Y/Z.

Recurring task examples:   
Screenshot competitor's landing pages and signup flows once per quarter, and put images in Dropbox folder with marked date.

**Area 15: Engineering**  
Activities relating to a company hiring engineers, developing or reviewing code, creating code with LLM or AI tools, and so on.

One-time task examples:   
Test flow X on Android, screenshot it, and report any bugs

Recurring task examples:   
Review bugs/feature requests each month and condense similar/repetitive ones into a cleaned list

**Area 16: Operations**  
General business operations which are not administrative, including customer support, fulfillment, etc.

One-time task examples:   
Set up an automation to monitor inventory and create a Slack message to X person if we go below some threshold

Recurring task examples:   
Create monthly update email with links to key metrics and curated quotes from customer calls

# **Delegation Scoring and Categorization with LLM Prompts**

Notes: 

* These represent initial drafts or example approaches, not extensively iterated final recommendations.   
* Once metadata is solidified (e.g. complexity vs scope vs some other aspect), prompts here may be improved with few shot examples for low, medium, and high scoring tasks.  
* Above each prompt would likely be some brief context on Athena and the use case at the very least, unless a fine-tuned model is used.

1. ## **Areas**

   1. Below is a task assigned to an EA. Please label it with an area from the below list. Output only the name of the area in your response, and nothing else. Do NOT say 'Area 3:' or 'Area:' before the label. Return only the label.,   
   2. \<categories\>\</categories\>  
   3. \<task\>  
      1. \<title\>\</title\>  
      2. \<details\>\</details\>  
   4. \</task\>

2. ## **Complexity**

   1. Below is a task assigned to an EA. Please give it a score for its complexity on a scale of 1 to 10\. 10 represents the most complex tasks one might assign to a world-class executive assistant. Output only a number in your response, and nothing else.

3. ## **Scope**

   1. Below is a task assigned to an EA. Please give it a score for its scope on a scale of 1 to 10\. 10 represents either extremely large-scale or atypical tasks one might assign to a world-class executive assistant whom they trust with the broadest set of personal and professional responsibilities. Output only a number in your response, and nothing else.

4. ## **Intimacy**

   1. Below is a task assigned to an EA. Please give it a score for its intimacy on a scale of 1 to 10\. 10 represents either extremely personal or extremely sensitive tasks one might assign to a world-class executive assistant whom they trust to the fullest extent, and where failure could be potentially catastrophic. Output only a number in your response, and nothing else.

5. ## **Tools or Account Access Required**

   1. Below is a \<task\> assigned to an EA. Please identify specific accounts that the EA would need to fulfill the requirements or request. If the task title or details include specific accounts like the name of a brokerage like IBKR, project management tool like Asana, or scheduling tool like Google Calendar, output these in your response. If a tool would be needed but the specific tool is unstated, provide a generic name like 'Calendar' or 'Email' for scheduling a meeting with someone. Output only a comma-separated list of accounts required in your response, and nothing else.

6. ## **One Time vs Recurring**

   1. Below is a \<task\> assigned to an EA. Please identify if this task is recurring based on its content or if it is similar to another task previously assigned in the list. Output only 'Recurring' or 'Non-Recurring' in your response, and nothing else.

## 

# **Delegation Pathways**

![][image2]

## **Defensive Delegation**

This involves handling tasks that have already been identified and are typically assigned to you via email, during a meeting, or through another channel. These tasks already exist within the framework of your responsibilities. While the nature of these tasks can be transformed or redefined, their existence and initial assignment are established.

### 

## **Offensive Delegation**

This type of delegation involves proactively identifying tasks that stem from broader goals or objectives. Unlike defensive delegation, these tasks are not assigned by someone else but are created to address unmet needs or to achieve strategic goals. The specifics of these tasks might not be fully defined, allowing for flexibility in execution. For example, an offensive delegation might involve instructing someone to research a topic, consult a particular expert, or explore solutions within a digital ecosystem.

## **Direct Delegation** 

This is the manual assignment of tasks, whether they are defensive or offensive. You personally handle the task identification and assignment process. For instance, manual defensive delegation might involve assigning a received email task to a team member. Manual offensive delegation could be asking a team member to develop a strategy based on company goals.

### 

## **Vicarious Delegation**

This involves delegating tasks indirectly through systems or intermediaries. This type of delegation reduces your active participation. For example, a vicarious defensive delegation might be using an AI system to triage emails and automatically assign tasks to relevant parties. Vicarious offensive delegation could involve empowering an assistant to devise and assign tasks based on a shared understanding of goals. This assistant, whether human or AI, operates with a degree of autonomy to manage and execute tasks based on predefined criteria.

## 

## **Delegation Matrix**

By combining these distinctions, we identify four types of delegation:

1. Direct Defensive Delegation  
   1. Directly assigning identified tasks that arrive in your areas of responsibility.  
2. Direct Offensive Delegation  
   1. Proactively defining and assigning tasks to meet strategic personal or professional goals.  
3. Vicarious Defensive Delegation  
   1. Utilizing systems or playbooks to have someone else handle incoming tasks without directly delegating each one.  
4. Vicarious Offensive Delegation  
   1. Empowering intermediaries to define and assign tasks based on broader goals and heuristics, including recursively (e.g. EA hires a dietician and chef).

# **Delegation Modalities**

1. ## **Ad hoc delegation** 

   *i.e. assigning a single task manually*

   1. Text  
      1. Via message, e.g. a WhatsApp text or email from client to EA  
      2. Via pulling into existing conversation or process, e.g. mentioning the EA on an email thread, in a Google Doc, or referring an EA to an action item mentioned in a call  
      3. Via task manager, e.g. ClickUp item assigned to EA, including when added via [quick capture](https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Eb3F7vIWkAEXVvg?format=jpg&name=4096x4096) or [sharing shortcut](https://res.cloudinary.com/imagist/image/fetch/q_auto,f_auto,c_scale,w_2624/https%3A%2F%2Ftdinspiration.wpengine.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2017%2F08%2Fadd-website-mobile.png)  
   2. Image  
      1. Typically a screenshot with a clearly implied task, usually sent via message or attached to task manager item  
   3. Audio  
      1. Voice note via Slack, WhatsApp, etc  
   4. Video  
      1. Loom video or similar  
      2. Zoom call between client and EA

2. ## **Process-driven delegation**

   *i.e. assigning a recurring task or workflow*

   1. Recurrence  
      1. Time-based recurrence  
         1. A documented process triggered by calendar, e.g. sending invoices at the end of a month, shopping for holiday gifts, booking a massage every 2 weeks, etc  
      2. Rules-based recurrence  
         1. An “if-then” process, e.g. when you buy a flight, create an Apple Note with the record locator and other details  
   2. Patterns  
      1. Playbook or standard operating procedure (SOP)  
         1. Development of process and documentation  
            1. Edit playbook/SOP from others, including Athena, templates found online, etc  
            2. Client creates playbook from scratch, written out or via Loom  
            3. EA creates playbook and asks for client review (with or without AI)  
            4. AI creates playbook draft by observing past instances of the process  
         2. Management and iteration of playbook or SOP  
      2. Automation, with or without human-in-the-loop (HITL)  
         1. Origination  
            1. Recurring task in task manager or calendar  
            2. Task triggered automatically via automation platform, such as Zapier   
               1. E.g. “when email arrives with these words”  
            3. Task triggered via specific platform  
               1. E.g. Ramp notification regarding a transaction that violates rules or breaks card limit  
         2. Implementation  
            1. Client identifies automation to copy or create  
            2. EA suggests automation to copy or create  
            3. AI may be involved in either case

3. ## **Goal-driven delegation**

   1. Areas of responsibility or goals  
      1. Client indicates they want help in a given area, e.g. recruiting or mental health, and encourages EA to look for opportunities to create leverage  
      2. Client defines an intent to hand off execution of a specific responsibility, e.g. which types of emails or email-related tasks the EA should handle at a high level, but doesn’t define every specific scenario  
      3. Client shares a specific goal outcome, e.g. losing X pounds by date Y or completing a fundraise by date Z, and empowers EA to suggest tasks or autonomously take action  
   2. Shared expectations and heuristics  
      1. Create a mutual understanding around desired approach to proactivity, e.g. how much or what type of tasks should be done without the client’s approval in various scenarios  
         1. Especially important when EA has access to areas where client responsibilities are generated, like visibility of the client’s task list, inbox, or call transcripts  
         2. Includes alignment on how much to spend to resolve a problem without verifying  
      2. Set a clear sense of which errors are acceptable byproducts of experimentation vs risks not to take, particularly around speed vs outcome tradeoffs  
         1. Aims to create an environment of psychological safety in ambiguous situations  
   3. Involvement of other people  
      1. Client enables others to assign work to the EA directly, rather than using client as intermediary

4. ## **Clairvoyant Delegation**

   1. Defensive / Need → action → playbook pathway  
      1. Suggestions  
         1. EA suggests potential tasks in area of responsibility or capability  
      2. Proactive performance  
         1. EA autonomously executes tasks based on shared understanding  
      3. Process enhancement  
         1. EA proactively suggests or implements process improvements  
      4. Systemization  
         1. EA recommends turning ad hoc tasks into process  
      5. Playbook creation  
         1. EA creates de novo playbooks for themselves and others  
   2. Offensive / Goal → idea → action pathway  
      1. Going Beyond  
         1. EA modifies & extends client's goal-driven delegations and processes  
      2. Suggested Delegations  
         1. EA offers own or researched ideas to accelerate client goals  
      3. Multiplayer Coordination  
         1. EA proactively supports, identifies, or involves known others in completing tasks related to goals  
      4. Conduit to Goal Personnel  
         1. EA recruits and acts as liaison with key experts and personnel (e.g. nutritionist, language tutor, property manager, co-founder, exec coach)  
      5. Full Deputization  
         1. EA co-owns goals and defines tasks/playbooks related to goals, with client-defined or EA-suggested limits

## **![][image3]**

5. ##  **AI delegation**

   1. Delegation Enhancement  
      1. Reformatting  
         1. AI converts messy or rambling voice note into clearer task description  
      2. Resource Attachment  
         1. AI finds relevant information to a delegated task, e.g. a Google Doc whose title is mentioned or contact information for a person listed  
      3. Risk Mitigation  
         1. AI flags potentially missing requirements or details that could prevent task execution  
      4. Co-Pilot  
         1. AI works synchronously with client during e.g. quarterly review, calendar/task audit, or ideation session  
         2. AI co-writes delegations in a task manager with contextual autocompletion or additions  
   2. Autodelegation  
      1. Email Autodelegation  
         1. AI identifies stated or implied tasks in email and creates an item in the task manager  
      2. Call Autodelegation  
         1. AI identifies stated or implied tasks in a call or meeting transcript and creates an item in the task manager  
      3. Screenshot Autodelegation  
         1. AI identifies stated or implied tasks in a screenshot and creates an item in the task manager  
   3. Delegation Suggestions  
      1. Goal-Based  
         1. AI suggests tasks for EA based on knowledge of clients’ goals, preferred strategies for pursuit, and other context  
         2. EA and/or client review for appropriateness  
      2. Activity-Based  
         1. AI reviews clients’ current actions, previously delegated tasks, and relevant context to suggest tasks the client could have delegated or should consider delegating  
         2. May include data from APIs (like calendar or task manager), activity logs (e.g. time-tracking applications), or screen recordings  
      3. Media-Based  
         1. AI reviews article, podcast, video, book, or other material and identifies how the client can imitate the strategy in an EA-forward approach  
         2. Previously referred to as the René Girard Autodelegator  
   4. Feedback & Coaching  
      1. Tactical improvement  
         1. Review delegated tasks and suggest improvements  
      2. Opportunities for standardization  
         1. Identify related delegations which can be converted into a playbook or clarified by a set of guidelines/heuristics  
      3. Gap identification  
         1. Flag areas where delegation is not occurring  
      4. Upskilling and advancement  
         1. Highlight potential areas where EA can expand responsibilities in scope or complexity  
         2. May include engaging external experts or contractors  
         3. Could involve identifying a resource related to a new skill, e.g. course or tutorial  
      5. Automation and process improvement  
         1. Identify EA tasks which can be implemented as an automated flow, e.g. via Zapier or AI agent  
         2. Consider ways to streamline or expand a process or recurring procedure

# **10 Core Delegation Skills**

![][image5]

1. Tactical Delegation & Task Assignment  
   1. Providing enough context about a task to facilitate performance while minimizing unnecessary clarifications and maximizing ability to execute in the broader context

2. Feedback & Coaching  
   1. Offering tactful assessment of how a task was not performed to expectations and establishing processes or heuristics to prevent a similar instance in the future

3. Goal & Task Decomposition  
   1. Breaking an abstract or complex goal or project into steps, then identifying where progress can be furthered by others (including EA, third party experts or contractors, teammates, friends/family, AI agents, software, etc)

4. System Design & Iteration  
   1. Transformation of recurring responsibilities into streamlined and structured processes, which are periodically reviewed and improved

5. Task & Project Management  
   1. Assignment and organization of work, along with the process by which tasks are prioritized, managed, and communicated

6. Context Creation & Cognitive Mise en Place  
   1. Systems design of the shared informational environment enabling better understanding and performance of work, plus creating ability to self-unblock by identifying where/how to close information gaps

7. Relationship Management & Interaction  
   1. Ability to establish and enhance trust, communication, collaboration, and mutual performance in the partnership

8. Reflection & Self-Improvement  
   1. Creative and analytical capacity to identify what is and isn’t working, where leverage is high vs low, and where opportunity costs of action or omission are limiting goal achievement; includes rituals which support this

9. Continuous Discovery & Scope Expansion  
   1. Practice of investigating new strategic or tactical approaches, studying the practices of others, and experimenting broadly with new learnings or in new areas

10. Emotional Management & Coping Strategies  
    1. System and tactics for confronting and surmounting challenges to progress arising from fear, anxiety, perfectionism, perceived loss of control, unhelpful beliefs, and related cognitive-emotional barriers
